Certainly! Below is an example of a simple web application that plays random high-frequency sinusoidal sounds when a button is clicked. The entire code is contained within a single HTML file, with embedded CSS and JavaScript.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random High Frequency Sinusoid Sounds</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        button {
            padding: 15px 30px;
            font-size: 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<button id="play-sound">Play Random High Frequency Sound</button>

<script>
    function playSinusoidalSound(frequency) {
        const audioCtx = new (window.AudioContext || window.webkitAudioContext)();
        const oscillator = audioCtx.createOscillator();

        oscillator.type = 'sine'; // Type of wave: sine
        oscillator.frequency.setValueAtTime(frequency, audioCtx.currentTime); // Frequency in Hz
        oscillator.connect(audioCtx.destination); // Connect to speakers
        oscillator.start();
        oscillator.stop(audioCtx.currentTime + 1); // Stop after 1 second
    }

    document.getElementById('play-sound').addEventListener('click', function() {
        const randomFrequency = Math.floor(Math.random() * (20000 - 10000 + 1)) + 10000; // Random frequency between 10 kHz and 20 kHz
        playSinusoidalSound(randomFrequency);
    });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use:
1. Copy the above code.
2. Paste it into a new file and save it with an `.html` extension, for example, `sound_player.html`.
3. Open the file in a web browser.
4. Click the "Play Random High Frequency Sound" button to hear random high-frequency sinusoidal sounds!

**Note:** The sound generated may not be audible on all devices, especially if the frequency is beyond the audible range for humans (typically 20 Hz to 20 kHz), and many speakers may not reproduce very high frequencies accurately.
